Date:  9/11/1852
Source:  NZ Government Gazette
Author:
Vol / Page:  V/26/165
Edition:
Quote:  ... a hole was dug ..., and a quantity of the soil washed, but without any visible satisfactory result ... [A] favourable indication was noticed at a bar in the creek, and a quantity of the gravel and earth removed, a panful was taken from about two feet below the surface and washed, it produced a number of scales of gold.
Notes:   (Report of Sub-Committee on Recent Gold Discovery in the Coromandel District)

Date:  10/12/1852
Source:  NZ Government Gazette
Author:
Vol / Page:   V/30/183
Edition:
Quote:  Kapanga River Diggings,/ Coromandel harbour,/ 4th November, 1852. ... the annexed tabular report of the work at this Gold-field since my arrival. ... wherever I and the Messrs. Ring have `prospected' on the Kapanga ..., we have found gold, and that the greatest number of flakes in the prospecting dish, appeared upon washing some earth yesterday at a bar about half a mile lower down the stream ...; and below all the present diggings.
Notes:  (Heaphy's Report)

Date:  10/12/1852
